454
00:46:26,909 --> 00:46:30,212
[SPEAKER_09]: That looks like the numbers add up there, sure.

455
00:46:31,453 --> 00:46:41,167
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, if you could share a little bit more about what you've been up to and what your plans are and other items that might need to be funded in the future.

456
00:46:41,720 --> 00:46:42,680
[SPEAKER_03]: Sure.

457
00:46:43,301 --> 00:46:45,402
[SPEAKER_03]: Basically, we're working still on infrastructure stuff.

458
00:46:46,502 --> 00:46:49,524
[SPEAKER_03]: We have 25 plus years of technical debt.

459
00:46:49,544 --> 00:46:50,784
[SPEAKER_03]: We're still trying to get out from under.

460
00:46:50,864 --> 00:46:52,645
[SPEAKER_03]: We're making progress all the time.

461
00:46:53,345 --> 00:46:55,266
[SPEAKER_03]: The hardest part is the foundational work.

462
00:46:55,566 --> 00:46:56,367
[SPEAKER_03]: It takes the longest.

463
00:46:56,447 --> 00:47:00,609
[SPEAKER_03]: It seems like you never move forward, but we're really close on a couple of big projects.

464
00:47:01,109 --> 00:47:04,090
[SPEAKER_03]: Entirely new network for City Hall.

465
00:47:04,651 --> 00:47:06,011
[SPEAKER_03]: That's going to be turning on pretty soon.

466
00:47:06,251 --> 00:47:09,793
[SPEAKER_03]: Actually, it's already running in parallel to the old stuff we've been testing.

467
00:47:11,001 --> 00:47:20,826
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the fiber network for the city in general, from all the municipal buildings, that's basically in place and being tested as we speak.

468
00:47:20,887 --> 00:47:22,507
[SPEAKER_03]: I've got some more infrastructure work to do.

469
00:47:23,008 --> 00:47:27,030
[SPEAKER_03]: The small data center we have, I'm testing that this week.

470
00:47:27,150 --> 00:47:36,195
[SPEAKER_03]: I have my fiber guys coming tomorrow to finish one last piece of fiber inside of a building, and then we'll start moving across rapidly.

471
00:47:37,300 --> 00:47:42,624
[SPEAKER_03]: Once that is done, then we can begin centralizing things.

472
00:47:42,824 --> 00:47:45,726
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is where you really get a lot of cost savings.

473
00:47:46,166 --> 00:47:49,088
[SPEAKER_03]: For instance, security systems, right?

474
00:47:49,169 --> 00:47:50,930
[SPEAKER_03]: Every building has its own today.

475
00:47:50,990 --> 00:47:51,991
[SPEAKER_03]: They're all really old.

476
00:47:52,051 --> 00:47:53,472
[SPEAKER_03]: I seem to start updating some of them.

477
00:47:54,893 --> 00:47:56,173
[SPEAKER_03]: I can centralize all that.

478
00:47:56,354 --> 00:48:03,339
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you're just putting sort of the endpoints out of the building, like cameras or what have you, or gate card readers.

479
00:48:04,219 --> 00:48:07,502
[SPEAKER_03]: where in the past you'd have to buy the whole surrounding infrastructure for that.

480
00:48:07,522 --> 00:48:13,789
[SPEAKER_03]: There's a box that goes on the wall, the cabling, the readers, it gets expensive, and then just the recorders themselves are super expensive.

481
00:48:14,229 --> 00:48:21,256
[SPEAKER_03]: So I can get away with doing one centralized for almost all of it and just putting what little endpoints I need at whatever locations we're doing there.

482
00:48:22,362 --> 00:48:26,806
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we have some server refreshes we have to think about.

483
00:48:27,626 --> 00:48:29,548
[SPEAKER_03]: We're still going to be on admins for a while.

484
00:48:30,308 --> 00:48:32,750
[SPEAKER_03]: That server is pretty much end of life.

485
00:48:33,470 --> 00:48:37,393
[SPEAKER_03]: And so is the Socrite server, which is our treasury server, which is where we collect all the money.

486
00:48:37,413 --> 00:48:41,056
[SPEAKER_03]: So we have to figure out how we're going to move those forward.

487
00:48:42,056 --> 00:48:44,578
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd like to do some other servers going away.

488
00:48:44,598 --> 00:48:49,202
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd like to collapse down as many applications as I can into a very small virtual environment.

489
00:48:49,262 --> 00:48:51,143
[SPEAKER_03]: That'll save a lot of money by doing it that way.

490
00:48:51,991 --> 00:48:54,552
[SPEAKER_03]: as some of those other applications will go away down the road.

491
00:48:56,233 --> 00:49:02,415
[SPEAKER_03]: And then Nina's favorite subject to always ask me about is new phones for City Hall.

492
00:49:03,475 --> 00:49:06,076
[SPEAKER_03]: Hopefully gonna happen in these sooner rather than later.

493
00:49:06,616 --> 00:49:09,758
[SPEAKER_03]: Every other department outside of City Hall is on them.

494
00:49:11,078 --> 00:49:12,219
[SPEAKER_03]: There are no problems.

495
00:49:12,259 --> 00:49:14,880
[SPEAKER_03]: They're all enjoying the capabilities and features.

496
00:49:14,900 --> 00:49:17,540
[SPEAKER_03]: It's been really great.

497
00:49:17,580 --> 00:49:18,721
[SPEAKER_03]: We've ironed out a lot

498
00:49:19,857 --> 00:49:25,862
[SPEAKER_03]: Of the transition issues, because the age of our systems by doing the other buildings and other departments 1st.

499
00:49:26,382 --> 00:49:29,305
[SPEAKER_03]: So, we'll go to do city hall should be pretty on eventful.

500
00:49:29,325 --> 00:49:29,725
[SPEAKER_03]: Hopefully.

501
00:49:30,926 --> 00:49:37,331
[SPEAKER_03]: But other than that, we just work on the usual stuff policy, the procedures, just try to mobilize some things for the every day so that.

502
00:49:38,112 --> 00:49:41,315
[SPEAKER_03]: When we get new hires, we can just hand them in the handbook.

503
00:49:41,815 --> 00:49:43,616
[SPEAKER_03]: This is how you attract with technology.

504
00:49:43,676 --> 00:49:44,317
[SPEAKER_03]: How do we use it?

505
00:49:44,357 --> 00:49:45,338
[SPEAKER_03]: We'll expect from you.

506
00:49:46,078 --> 00:49:47,900
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, so our security and things like that.

507
00:49:49,488 --> 00:49:52,032
[SPEAKER_03]: But that's all the back end boring stuff.

508
00:49:52,493 --> 00:49:55,338
[SPEAKER_03]: As far as funding goes, you know, future projects.

509
00:49:57,141 --> 00:50:00,106
[SPEAKER_03]: The way my budget works now is that

510
00:50:01,607 --> 00:50:04,750
[SPEAKER_03]: being a one-person shop, you can only take on so many products, whatever you want.

511
00:50:04,990 --> 00:50:08,914
[SPEAKER_03]: If you ask any department head, they go up there and they're going to say, yes, I have 10 more projects I can do.

512
00:50:09,014 --> 00:50:13,818
[SPEAKER_03]: But you have to be pragmatic about these things and say, how much can I get done in one fiscal year?

513
00:50:13,838 --> 00:50:16,621
[SPEAKER_03]: Because some of these projects have long time frames.

514
00:50:16,681 --> 00:50:20,685
[SPEAKER_03]: And I try to, the bigger project, maybe cross across two fiscal years.

515
00:50:22,106 --> 00:50:26,807
[SPEAKER_03]: So I feel like I have the money to do what I want barring something catastrophic happening.

516
00:50:28,528 --> 00:50:30,868
[SPEAKER_03]: But I do have a lot of products built in there.

517
00:50:30,908 --> 00:50:38,930
[SPEAKER_03]: I just don't see myself needing to come to you guys for stabilization funding or just my products aren't that big ticket item anymore.

518
00:50:42,531 --> 00:50:42,852
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

519
00:50:43,012 --> 00:50:43,472
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

520
00:50:43,492 --> 00:50:44,572
[SPEAKER_09]: I will go to Councillor Lemming.

521
00:50:46,424 --> 00:50:53,366
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you and thank you for keeping the entirety of the city's IT on your back.

522
00:50:55,246 --> 00:51:02,368
[SPEAKER_07]: It is really miraculous how you're able to do this job as a one man department, so very much appreciated.

523
00:51:02,388 --> 00:51:05,308
[SPEAKER_07]: I would like to ask, is

524
00:51:08,949 --> 00:51:15,456
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry, what's the status of the phishing emails within the city?

525
00:51:15,496 --> 00:51:24,844
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I get a good amount of emails from Isaac Bears asking for a five-minute meeting.

526
00:51:24,864 --> 00:51:28,468
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's not actually from him.

527
00:51:28,488 --> 00:51:31,230
[SPEAKER_07]: He never sends me the gift card.

528
00:51:31,350 --> 00:51:32,171
[SPEAKER_09]: He never sends it.

529
00:51:32,311 --> 00:51:32,792
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know why.

530
00:51:34,918 --> 00:51:37,166
[SPEAKER_07]: It's always I'm rushing to a meeting.

531
00:51:37,186 --> 00:51:38,450
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you have 5 minutes of talk?

532
00:51:38,490 --> 00:51:40,737
[SPEAKER_07]: Just reply to this email kind of things and.

533
00:51:41,637 --> 00:51:56,361
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, I'm, it concerns me not because I've ever tried to respond to those, but reading about the case, I think it was in Arlington where they lost quite a bit of money because somebody fell for 1 of those things.

534
00:51:57,621 --> 00:51:59,462
[SPEAKER_07]: So, I'm just like, wondering if your.

535
00:52:00,142 --> 00:52:10,805
[SPEAKER_07]: Fingers on the pulse of of that of that issue, and if there have been any incidents that have been memorable around city hall where some employees might have fallen for that.

536
00:52:11,565 --> 00:52:12,325
[SPEAKER_03]: No, we're pretty good.

537
00:52:12,345 --> 00:52:17,608
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I talk to the employees all the time about it and have them trained up pretty well on how to spot them.

538
00:52:18,868 --> 00:52:23,771
[SPEAKER_03]: And if they have any questions, they'll just send it right to me and say, is this really from whomever?

539
00:52:24,531 --> 00:52:27,052
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'll go down and just point out all the flaws in it.

540
00:52:27,412 --> 00:52:28,393
[SPEAKER_03]: And they usually catch on.

541
00:52:28,573 --> 00:52:30,394
[SPEAKER_03]: And we haven't had any incidents.

542
00:52:31,058 --> 00:52:40,608
[SPEAKER_03]: that 99% of the time, or 90% of the incidents that happen out there aren't from a phishing email or somebody clicking on a link they shouldn't have.

543
00:52:40,628 --> 00:52:43,631
[SPEAKER_03]: They're from somebody calling and pretending to be someone else.

544
00:52:43,731 --> 00:52:45,012
[SPEAKER_03]: Social engineering, it's called.

545
00:52:46,353 --> 00:52:47,595
[SPEAKER_03]: That's what happened to Arlington.

546
00:52:48,515 --> 00:52:54,161
[SPEAKER_03]: Not to reveal too much, but it wasn't because of an email or anything like that.

547
00:52:54,181 --> 00:52:54,842
[SPEAKER_03]: There were some other

548
00:52:55,355 --> 00:52:56,455
[SPEAKER_03]: things that went on there.

549
00:52:57,616 --> 00:53:10,300
[SPEAKER_03]: I took the lessons learned from that and went to the people of the department here, the corollary department, explained to them what happened, what they should look for, and what have you, so it won't happen here, that type of thing.

550
00:53:10,960 --> 00:53:12,281
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, it's the same thing.

551
00:53:12,341 --> 00:53:14,563
[SPEAKER_03]: I get so much spam, it's ridiculous.

552
00:53:15,123 --> 00:53:16,304
[SPEAKER_03]: But then it ebbs and flows.

553
00:53:16,324 --> 00:53:19,106
[SPEAKER_03]: And as soon as you shut off one avenue, they pick up another one.

554
00:53:19,606 --> 00:53:21,247
[SPEAKER_03]: This is all robotic, right?

555
00:53:21,287 --> 00:53:22,228
[SPEAKER_03]: It's all just automation.

556
00:53:22,248 --> 00:53:31,634
[SPEAKER_03]: They're creating hundreds of thousands of fake email addresses a day and just scraping the website, seeing all the names of the people, your treasurer, Judy Johnson.

557
00:53:31,654 --> 00:53:33,215
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm going to send a Judy Johnson

558
00:53:34,096 --> 00:53:52,422
[SPEAKER_03]: very official looking thing you know here's the invoice you're looking for or what have you if she's doing 100 things in a day like she usually is maybe it gets through when she clicks on the pdf or what have you that's what they're banking on it's this mass mailing type of thing that goes on but what i've seen really the

559
00:53:53,925 --> 00:54:01,572
[SPEAKER_03]: The biggest people they get caught up by, it's usually the schools and police departments, to be honest with you.

560
00:54:01,972 --> 00:54:08,318
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think anyone finds, you know, the veteran services office that interested.

561
00:54:08,338 --> 00:54:13,262
[SPEAKER_03]: They're going to have a coordinated campaign against them in particular type of thing.

562
00:54:14,604 --> 00:54:25,685
[SPEAKER_03]: What they're going for is either locking you out of everything and then ransomware, obviously, or just something that makes the news, that raises their name up there further in the hacker community.

563
00:54:26,532 --> 00:54:27,833
[SPEAKER_03]: But no, we do a really good job.

564
00:54:27,873 --> 00:54:28,733
[SPEAKER_03]: We've had trainings.

565
00:54:30,214 --> 00:54:33,435
[SPEAKER_03]: I have good faith in people doing the right thing.

566
00:54:33,475 --> 00:54:37,176
[SPEAKER_03]: I just had somebody send me one today that was actually laughing about it.

567
00:54:37,236 --> 00:54:44,639
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, and somebody that isn't the most sophisticated computer user, but since I've shown them how to spot them, they actually, it's like a little game for them.

568
00:54:45,079 --> 00:54:48,481
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, they send them on and we just have it blacklisted, but it's almost meaningless.

569
00:54:49,341 --> 00:54:53,423
[SPEAKER_03]: We do have a pretty good spam slash phishing email.

570
00:54:54,623 --> 00:54:59,086
[SPEAKER_03]: filter on the front end, before emails even hit inboxes, does a pretty good job.

571
00:54:59,107 --> 00:55:05,491
[SPEAKER_03]: But again, they're as fast as we tweak that, they're tweaking in a different direction and getting through in some instances.

572
00:55:05,531 --> 00:55:13,097
[SPEAKER_03]: But if you saw the numbers of emails that never made it to desktops, it's the numbers that make it are minuscule out of the total.

573
00:55:13,117 --> 00:55:19,262
[SPEAKER_09]: All right, I'll go to Councilor Sang.

574
00:55:20,913 --> 00:55:21,553
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi there, Rich.

575
00:55:22,614 --> 00:55:30,636
[SPEAKER_02]: You mentioned that we're backfilling a lot of things that used to be funded with federal funds with grants.

576
00:55:31,837 --> 00:55:38,439
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm curious as to what grants we are already taking advantage of.

577
00:55:38,599 --> 00:55:49,903
[SPEAKER_02]: Are there any out there that we haven't applied for yet that we could apply for to help with funding these programs and funding maybe future programming?

578
00:55:50,862 --> 00:55:54,163
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so maybe I should have been a little more detailed.

579
00:55:54,443 --> 00:55:57,984
[SPEAKER_03]: The money that I was talking about as far as my budget was opera money that fell off.

580
00:55:58,304 --> 00:55:59,725
